    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-07-14T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-07-14T22:00:00-05:00" n="342"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d342">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">715.1715/377: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-07-14T21:00:00-06:00"
                            >July 14, 1930—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 16—10:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>60. The following telegram was sent to Nicaragua, July 14, 9 p.m.: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Your July 9, 3 p.m., to the Department. The Minister for Foreign Affairs
                            informs me that Honduran Government would have no objection to the
                            additional provision mentioned in your telegram. He intimated that the
                            President desires that the protocol be signed at an early date and in
                            Tegucigalpa. Would the Government of Nicaragua be disposed to accept an
                            invitation direct from Honduras to sign the protocol at Tegucigalpa? If
                            so, at the appropriate time I can suggest to President that he extend
                            such an invitation. An invitation was extended to Honduras to sign a
                            similar protocol here (see your telegram of November 8, 3 p.m., 1929, to
                            the Department<note n="92" xml:id="d342fn92">
                                <ref target="frus1929v01#pg_983">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1929, vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 983</ref>.</note>).”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
